Today, I explored device security and network protection to understand how to secure computing devices from potential threats. Here are my key takeaways:
ğŸ”¹ 1. Open Ports: The Hidden Entry Points

Every network-based service runs on a specific port number (e.g., HTTP â†’ Port 80, SSH â†’ Port 22). If a service is not in use, keeping the port open is a security risk. Attackers can scan for open ports and exploit vulnerabilities.
ğŸ›¡ Solution: Regularly check for open ports using tools like nmap and close any unused ones.
ğŸ”¹ 2. Firewalls: Your First Line of Defense

A firewall helps control which devices or services can communicate with your system. You can configure rules to allow or deny traffic based on IP addresses, ports, or applications.
âœ… Example: Allow only your internal network to access a database server while blocking external access.
ğŸ”¹ 3. Default Credentials = Easy Target

Many network devices (routers, switches, firewalls) come with default usernames and passwords like admin/admin. Attackers know these defaults and can use them to gain access.
ğŸ›¡ Solution: Change all default credentials immediately after setup. Check routerpasswords.com to see if your device's default login is public knowledge.
ğŸ”¹ 4. Port Security & Network Access Control (NAC)

ğŸ” Port Security (used in network switches) ensures that only authorized devices can connect. It works by binding MAC addresses to specific switch ports, preventing unauthorized access.
ğŸ”‘ Network Access Control (802.1X) adds authentication, requiring users to log in before accessing the network.
ğŸ”¹ 5. MAC Filtering: Not Foolproof

A MAC address is a deviceâ€™s unique hardware address. Many networks use MAC filtering to block unauthorized devices.
ğŸš¨ Risk: MAC addresses can be spoofed (changed using software), allowing an attacker to bypass this security.
âœ… Better approach: Use multi-factor authentication and encryption instead of relying solely on MAC filtering.
